0.description: Amanita with white spore print, gills attached to stem, cap diameter up to 10 cm.

1.description: A deciduous conifer with soft yellow-green needles and long, cylindrical cones.

2.description: Amanita olivaceogrisea is a species of Amanita found in England, Estonia, France, Latvia, and Sweden.

3.description: Small, pale brown cap with pinkish tinge, white gills, white spore print.

4.description: Russula mustelina, commonly known as the russet brittlegill, is a basidiomycete mushroom of the genus Russula native to Europe and North America. Swedish mycologist Elias Magnus Fries described the species in his 1838 book Epicrisis Systematis Mycologici seu Synopsis Hymenomycetum.

5.description: Amanita regalis, commonly known as the royal fly agaric or the king of Sweden Amanita, is a species of fungus in the family Amanitaceae. A. regalis has a scabby liver-brown cap and a stem which is yellow-ochre at the base, with patches or rings of patches. The fruit bodies somewhat resemble the smaller A. muscaria, which it was formerly regarded as a variety of.

6.description: Perennial herb with blue to purple flowers and dark red roots.

7.description: Large, plump gamebird with distinctive head crest, brown plumage, and long tail.

9.description: Mycena epipterygia is a species of fungus in the family Mycenaceae of mushrooms commonly found in Europe. It is commonly known as yellowleg bonnet or yellow-stemmed mycena. Mycena nivicola has been suggested as a separate species name for the Western variety.

11.description: A large tree with rough, furrowed bark and lobed leaves.

12.description: Small beetle with two black spots on a reddish-brown body.

13.description: A large deciduous tree with rough brown bark and lobed leaves.

14.description: A flowering plant with purple flowers and green foliage.

15.description: Black and yellow striped bee, important pollinator.

16.description: A large deciduous tree with wide spreading branches and distinctive lobed leaves.

17.description: Deciduous conifer with soft yellow-green needles and long, cylindrical cones.

18.description: Small to medium-sized carnivorous mammal, reddish fur, bushy tail.

19.description: Large white butterfly with black markings, wingspan about 75mm.

20.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

21.description: Black and yellow striped bee, important for pollination.

22.description: Russula maculata is a species of mushroom in the genus Russula. Its cap ranges from 4–10 centimetres wide, with hues varying from whitish to red. It is difficult to distinguish reliably and its edibility is unknown.

23.description: Large butterfly with greenish-yellow wings and black markings.

24.description: Russula laeta is a brittle gill species that was first described by Julius Schäffer in 1952. This species is critically endangered in Belgium.

25.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, small, greenish-yellow flowers.

27.description: Deciduous tree with small, round leaves that tremble in the wind and white bark.

28.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

29.description: Large evergreen tree, brown bark, alternate leaves, small acorns.

30.description: Small, herbaceous plant with purple roots and blue flowers.

31.description: Spiny shrub with white flowers, large spines, creamy sap, native to arid regions of Namibia and South Africa.

32.description: Quercus robur, with distinctive lobed leaves and serrated margins. Gray, deeply furrowed bark. Can grow up to 35 meters tall.

33.description: feathery plumes, heart-shaped leaves, climbing plant, up to 6 meters tall

34.description: A small beetle with black and red markings and long antennae.

35.description: Black body with yellow legs and pale yellow bands on abdomen.

36.description: Spiny shrub with red bracts and green leaves.

37.description: Russula vinosa, commonly known as the darkening brittlegill, is a species of basidiomycete mushroom found in coniferous woodlands in Europe and North America in summer and early autumn. Unlike many red-capped members of the russula genus, it is edible and mild-tasting. It is usually understood to have a symbiotic relationship with evergreen tree roots, except for in mountainous areas where it has occasionally associated with birches.

38.description: A large beetle with black and red markings and very long antennae.

39.description: Russula acrifolia is a species of mushroom. Its cap is coloured grey to blackish-grey; the cap becomes red when it is injured, but then turns blackish-gray. It is edible and described as having an acrid taste. It grows on rich soils.

40.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped flowers.

41.description: Small to medium-sized beetle, brown to black in color, with two distinct yellow spots on wing covers.

42.description: Deciduous conifer, needles in bundles of 2, drooping branches, brown cones

43.description: The mushroom Russula gracillima, commonly known as the slender brittlegill, is a member of the genus Russula, whose members are commonly known as brittlegills. It is a small, pale, long stemmed brittlegill associated mainly with birch and is occasional in Europe, Asia, and North America.

44.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

45.description: A small fly with distinct red and gray markings on its abdomen.

46.description: Green beetle with metallic sheen and clear wings.

47.description: A large tree with rough, furrowed bark and lobed leaves.

49.description: White mushroom with convex cap, smooth surface, small size.

50.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves, small green flowers in panicles, and winged seeds.

51.description: A small beetle with two black spots on its back and elongated body.

52.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

53.description: A small beetle with black and red markings and long antennae.

54.description: Black and yellow striped bee, important for pollination.

55.description: Large, plump bird with distinctive black and white plumage, long tail, and prominent crest.

56.description: Leaves: lobed, alternate, green; acorns: solitary, cupped by a shallow cup.

57.description: A flowering plant with purple flowers and green foliage.

58.description: Large white mushroom with gills on underside of cap, about 5cm diameter.

59.description: Deciduous shrub with sharp prickles, pink to white flowers, and bright red hips.

60.description: Small carnivorous mammal with soft fur, pointed ears, and retractable claws.

62.description: Russula illota is an inedible species of mushroom in the genus Russula. It is commonly found in deciduous and coniferous forests on chalk.

64.description: Deciduous conifer with soft needles and distinctive drooping branches.

65.description: Low-growing shrub with dark green leaves and small, blue berries.

66.description: Medium-sized tree with heart-shaped leaves and drooping catkins.

67.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, small, greenish-yellow flowers.

68.description: Large deciduous tree with large leaves and distinctive bark.

69.description: Large, plump gamebird with long tail, barred breast, and distinctive crest.

71.description: Small herb with purple flowers and fleshy roots.

72.description: Medium-sized canine with reddish fur, black-tipped tail, and pointed ears.

73.description: Clitocybe agrestis is a species of agaric fungus. Widely distributed in Europe, it was described as new to science in 1969 by the Finnish mycologist Harri Harmaja. Fruitbodies are poisonous as they contain the toxin muscarine.

75.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and clusters of small, fragrant white flowers.

76.description: Fruit flies have distinctive red eyes and a black body with distinct cross-striations. They are about 2-3 mm in length.

77.description: Mycena purpureofusca, commonly known as the purple edge bonnet, is a species of agaric fungus in the family Mycenaceae. First described by Charles Horton Peck in 1885, The mushroom is named for the characteristic dark greyish-purple color of its gill edges.

78.description: Russula pseudointegra is an inedible, quite rare mushroom of the genus Russula, with a similar habitat and appearance to Russula rosea. Russula pseudointegra is distinguished by its hot tasting flesh.

79.description: Clitocybe vibecina is a common, inedible mushroom of the genus Clitocybe. It often grows in rings on needle litter, usually late in the year.

81.description: Agaricus moelleri, commonly known as the inky mushroom, or dark scaled mushroom, is a large species of fungus in the genus Agaricus. It appears occasionally in most kinds of woodland, during late summer, in northern temperate zones.

82.description: A large, long-lived deciduous tree with lobed leaves and acorns in cup-like structures.

83.description: Deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped flowers.

84.description: Small, dark purple flowering plant with hairy stems.

85.description: Russula sanguinaria, commonly known as the bloody brittlegill or rosey russula, is a strikingly coloured mushroom of the genus Russula, which has the common name of brittlegills. It is bright blood-red, inedible, and grows in association with coniferous trees. It was previously widely known as Russula sanguinea.

86.description: A large deciduous tree with smooth gray bark and distinctive lobed leaves.

87.description: Large, plump gamebird with long tail, barred breast, and distinctive crest.

89.description: Shrub or small tree with tendrils. Oval leaves with serrated edges. Small berries in clusters.

90.description: Tilia cordata, known as Small-leaved Lime, has heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped flowers. It is a deciduous tree.

91.description: Small, brown cap; white spore print; gills attached to stem.

92.description: Small grayish mushrooms with caps up to 1.5 cm wide, atop stipes 5 cm long and 2.5 mm thick. Grayish-white adnate gills with a 'tooth' running down the stipe.

95.description: Russula decolorans, commonly known as the graying russula, is a Russula mushroom found in forests. Although edible, it resembles several questionable species.

96.description: Small, dark beetle; elongated body; distinctive orange markings on wing covers.

97.description: Quercus robur is a large deciduous tree with distinctive lobed leaves.

98.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and drooping catkins.

99.description: Russula graveolens is an edible species of fungus in the genus Russula. The species was first officially described by Swedish mycologist Lars Romell in 1893.

102.description: Low-growing shrub, dark purple berries, evergreen leaves.

103.description: A large tree with reddish-brown bark and lobed leaves.

105.description: Brown cap 5–12 cm across with charcoal-grey patches. White stipe 7–18 cm long, tapering to top with irregular cottony bands at base.

106.description: Russula versicolor is a mushroom in the genus Russula. It is considered inedible.

107.description: A small to medium-sized beetle with a shiny black body and distinct yellow markings on the pronotum.

108.description: Large ground-dwelling bird with long tail and distinctive plumage.

109.description: Perennial herb with purple flowers and fleshy roots.

111.description: Small, herbaceous plant with purple roots and blue flowers.

112.description: Perennial plant with purple flowers and distinctive red roots.

114.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

115.description: Large tree with broad leaves and acorns.

117.description: Large, ground-dwelling bird with glossy black upperparts, red face, and long tail.

118.description: Russula amoenolens, also known by its common name camembert brittlegill, is a member of the genus Russula. The species has a greyish-brown cap, with clear scoring along the edge. While inedible, the mushroom is known for its distinctive smell like camembert cheese. The mushroom often appears under oak trees from summer to autumn.

119.description: A deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

122.description: Agaricus silvaticus, otherwise known as the scaly wood mushroom, blushing wood mushroom, or pinewood mushroom, is a species of mushroom often found in groups in coniferous forests from early summer, or September through to November in Europe, North Africa and North America.

123.description: White mushroom with convex cap, smooth surface, small size.

124.description: The edible wild mushroom Russula heterophylla, that has lately been given the common name of the greasy green brittlegill is placed in the genus Russula, the members of which are mostly known as brittlegills. It is a variably colored mushroom, found in deciduous forests, and woods in Britain, Europe, and Scandinavia. Appearing with broad-leaved trees in summer to early autumn, it usually has a greenish coloration.

126.description: A large, ground-dwelling bird with distinctive plumage and a long tail.

127.description: Small butterfly with greenish-blue wings, black markings, and a wingspan of about 50mm.

128.description: Collybia phyllophila, commonly known as the frosty funnel or the leaf-loving clitocybe, is a fungus in the family Tricholomataceae. Its epithet, meaning leaf-loving comes from its preference for leaf litter. It is common among forests in the Northern Hemisphere, and is poisonous.

129.description: Russula grata is a species of fungus belonging to the family Russulaceae.

130.description: Picea abies is a large evergreen conifer with dark green needles and short, thick twigs. Can grow up to 50 meters tall.

132.description: Picea abies, Norway spruce, conical evergreen conifer with gray-brown, fissured bark and bluish-green, stiff needles with sharp tips.

133.description: Clitocybe odora, commonly known as the blue green anise mushroom, or aniseed toadstool, is a blue-green mushroom that smells strongly like anise. It grows near deciduous and coniferous trees, in small groups alongside tree roots. This mushroom is edible but may resemble poisonous species.

134.description: Clematis vitalba, with pinnate leaves of 5-13 leaflets and small white flowers in dense clusters. Long, silky-haired fruits.

135.description: The mushroom Russula fellea goes by the common name of the geranium-scented russula, or bitter russula and is a member of the genus Russula, all of which are commonly known as brittlegills. It is straw or honey coloured and in Britain grows in beech woods during autumn. It is inedible.

136.description: Green cap, white spores, gills attached to stem.

137.description: Cap: Small, white, dusted with sugar-like granules; up to 5 mm in diameter. Stem: Thin, hollow, up to 15 mm long, set on a disc-like base.

138.description: Russula virescens is a basidiomycete mushroom of the genus Russula, and is commonly known as the green-cracking russula, the quilted green russula, or the green brittlegill. The species was described as new to science in 1774 by Jacob Christian Schaeffer. It can be recognized by its distinctive pale green cap that measures up to 15 cm (6 in) in diameter, the surface of which is covered with darker green angular patches. It has crowded white gills, and a firm, white stipe that is up to 8 cm (3 in) tall and 4 cm (1.6 in) thick. It resembles species such as Russula parvovirescens and R. crustosa.

139.description: Mycena arcangeliana is a species of Mycenaceae fungus. It has been known by a number of scientific names, and its taxonomy is still somewhat disputed. It produces small mushrooms with caps varying in colour from whitish to a darker grey-brown, and stems of an olive-greyish that fade with age. The mushrooms can be mistaken for the similar Mycena flavescens. They have a mild taste, but a strong smell of iodoform; they are not edible. The species grows on dead wood in autumn months, and can be found throughout Europe.

140.description: A medium-sized tree with heart-shaped leaves and fragrant, star-shaped yellow flowers.

141.description: Formerly Russula mairei (Singer), and commonly known as the beechwood sickener, the now re-classified fungus Russula nobilis (Velen.) is a basidiomycete mushroom of the genus Russula. This group of mushrooms are noted for their brittle gills and bright colours.

142.description: Mycena metata is a species of fungus in the family Mycenaceae found in Europe. It is inedible.

143.description: Tilia cordata, a deciduous tree with heart-shaped leaves and clusters of small, fragrant flowers.

145.description: Clitocybe nebularis or Lepista nebularis, commonly known as the clouded agaric, cloudy clitocybe, or cloud funnel, is an abundant gilled fungus which appears both in conifer-dominated forests and broad-leaved woodland in Europe and North America. Appearing in Britain from mid to late autumn, it is edible, but may cause gastrointestinal issues.

146.description: Russula claroflava, commonly known as the yellow russula, yellow swamp russula or yellow swamp brittlegill, is a basidiomycete mushroom of the genus Russula. It has a yellow cap, white gills and stipe and bruises grey.

147.description: Agaricus silvicola, also known as the wood mushroom or woodland agaricus, is a species of Agaricus mushroom related to the button mushroom.

149.description: Russula atropurpurea is an edible member of the genus Russula. It is dark vinaceous or purple, and grows with deciduous, or occasionally coniferous trees. It is commonly called the blackish purple Russula, or the purple brittlegill.

150.description: Russula violeipes, commonly known as the velvet brittlegill, is a species of fungus in the family Russulaceae. It was described by French mycologist Lucien Quélet in 1898. An edible mushroom, it is found in Asia and Europe.

151.description: Russula foetens, commonly known as the stinking russula, is a common Russula mushroom found in deciduous and coniferous forests.

153.description: Russula queletii otherwise known as the gooseberry russula, is a common, inedible, Russula mushroom found growing in groups, predominantly in spruce forest. Eating this mushroom causes abdominal pains.

154.description: Mycena leptocephala, commonly known as the nitrous bonnet, is a species of fungus in the family Mycenaceae. The mushrooms have conical grayish caps that reach up to 3 cm (1.2 in) in diameter, and thin fragile stems up to 5 cm (2.0 in) long. The gills are gray and distantly spaced. The spores are elliptical, typically measure 7–10 by 4–6 μm, and are white in deposit. When viewed under a light microscope, the gills have abundant spindle-shaped cystidia on the gill edges, but few on the gill faces. Similar species include Mycena alcalina, M. austera, and M. brevipes.

155.description: Mycena inclinata has a reddish-brown bell-shaped cap up to 4.5 cm in diameter. The thin stem is up to 9 cm tall, whitish to yellow-brown at the top, becoming reddish-brown towards the base, where it is covered by a yellowish mycelium. Gills are pale brown to pinkish.

156.description: Canada thistle, purple-tinted, with small pink flowers and deeply lobed leaves forming dense mats.

157.description: Dendroctonus valens is a small beetle. It is reddish-brown with two distinct spots on its back.

158.description: Mycena sanguinolenta, with conic to bell-shaped reddish-brown to reddish-purple caps up to 1.5 cm wide, held by slender stipes up to 6 cm high. Produces dark reddish-purple sap when fresh.

159.description: Deciduous conifer with soft needles in clusters of two, small cones.

160.description: Mycena polygramma, small pale gray-brown mushroom with broadly conical caps and pinkish gills, found on stumps and branches of deciduous and coniferous trees.

161.description: Perennial herb with purple flowers and lance-shaped leaves.

162.description: Amanita virosa is a species of fungus in the class Agaricomycetes. In the UK, it has the recommended English name of destroying angel and is known internationally as the European destroying angel. Basidiocarps are agaricoid (mushroom-shaped) and pure white with a ring on the stem and a sack-like volva at the base.

163.description: Russula rosea, known as the rosy russula, is a north temperate, commonly found mushroom of the large "brittlegill" genus Russula.

165.description: Dendroctonus valens, southern two-spotted bark beetle, black and yellow markings, about 4 mm long.

166.description: Mycena galopus, commonly known as the milky mycena, milking bonnet or milk-drop mycena, is an inedible species of fungus in the family Mycenaceae of the order Agaricales. It produces small mushrooms that have grayish-brown, bell-shaped, radially-grooved caps up to 2.5 cm (1 in) wide. The gills are whitish to gray, widely spaced, and squarely attached to the stem. The slender stems are up to 8 cm (3 in) long, and pale gray at the top, becoming almost black at the hairy base. The stem will ooze a whitish latex if it is injured or broken. The variety nigra has a dark gray cap, while the variety candida is white. All varieties of the mushroom occur during summer and autumn on leaf litter in coniferous and deciduous habitats.

167.description: Agaricus bitorquis, commonly known as torq, banded agaric, spring agaric, banded agaricus, urban agaricus, or pavement mushroom, is an edible white mushroom of the genus Agaricus, similar to the common button mushroom that is sold commercially. The name supersedes Agaricus rodmani.

169.description: Large, ground-dwelling bird with glossy black upperparts, red wattles, and long tail.

171.description: Mycena tintinnabulum is a European species of agaric fungus in the family Mycenaceae. The mycelium, but not the fruit body, is bioluminescent.

172.description: Pale yellow or white cap, white stem, ring, and volva.

173.description: Mycena epipterygia is a species of fungus in the family Mycenaceae of mushrooms commonly found in Europe. It is commonly known as yellowleg bonnet or yellow-stemmed mycena. Mycena nivicola has been suggested as a separate species name for the Western variety.

175.description: Small brown mushroom, up to 5 cm diameter, white gills, white stem.

177.description: Quercus robur, a deciduous tree, with large, lobed leaves and acorns.

178.description: Amanita phalloides, known as the death cap, features a large, convex cap that can be greenish to yellowish in color, with a white spore print and a white, equal-stem.

179.description: Agaricus xanthodermus, yellow-staining milk cap, mushroom-forming fungus, genus Agaricus.

182.description: Agaricus campestris is a widely eaten gilled mushroom closely related to the cultivated A. bisporus. A. campestris is commonly known as the field mushroom or, in North America, meadow mushroom.

183.description: Clitocybe fragrans is a species of mushroom with several lookalikes, some of which are poisonous.

185.description: Mycena crocata is a species of agaric fungus in the family Mycenaceae. The common name saffrondrop bonnet refers to the red or orange latex that it exudes if the stipe is broken. Its habitat is woody debris and leaf litter in deciduous woodland, especially beech.

187.description: Russula adusta, commonly known as the blackening brittlegill or blackening russula, is a species of gilled mushroom. It is a member of the Russula subgenus Compactae. The cap is brown to gray and somewhat shiny, with a mild taste and, reportedly, an odor of empty wine barrels. It has a propensity to turn black from cutting or bruising and has white spores. Similar species include Russula albonigra and R. densifolia.

188.description: Mycena rosea, commonly known as the rosy bonnet, is a species of bioluminescent mushroom in the family Mycenaceae. First named Agaricus roseus in 1803 by Danish botanist Heinrich Christian Friedrich Schumacher, it was given its present name in 1912 by Gramberg.

189.description: Russula ochroleuca is a member of the genus Russula. A group that have become known as brittlegills. It has been commonly known as the common yellow russula for some years, and latterly the ochre brittlegill. It is widespread, and common in mixed woodland.

191.description: The blusher is the common name for several closely related species of the genus Amanita. A. rubescens is found in Eurasia and A. novinupta is found in western North America. Both their scientific and common names stem from the tendency of their flesh to bruise pink.

192.description: Clitocybe nebularis or Lepista nebularis, commonly known as the clouded agaric, cloudy clitocybe, or cloud funnel, is an abundant gilled fungus which appears both in conifer-dominated forests and broad-leaved woodland in Europe and North America. Appearing in Britain from mid to late autumn, it is edible, but may cause gastrointestinal issues.

193.description: Mycena galericulata is a mushroom species commonly known as the common bonnet, the toque mycena, the common mycena or the rosy-gill fairy helmet. The type species of the genus Mycena was first described scientifically in 1772, but was not considered a Mycena until 1821.

194.description: Amanita muscaria, commonly known as the fly agaric or fly amanita, is a basidiomycete fungus of the genus Amanita. It is a large white-gilled, white-spotted mushroom typically featuring a bright red cap covered with distinctive white warts. It is one of the most recognisable fungi in the world.

195.description: Felis catus, a small cat with soft fur, pointed ears, and a distinctive whisker pattern.
